    "### I. Exercices Numpy\n",
    "\n",
    "Pour s'entrainer, des exercices avec solutions sont disponible [ici](https://www.machinelearningplus.com/python/101-numpy-exercises-python/).\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Créez un array avec les entiers 0 à 10 et générez en sortie un array où les valeurs impaires de l'array ont été remplacées par des -1.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Sortie désirée : ```array([ 0, -1, 2, -1, 4, -1, 6, -1, 8, -1, 10])```\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "42f635e0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "l = np.arange(1001)\n"

   "source": [

    "2. Créez un array avec les entiers de 0 à 100 et générez en sortie un array contenant seulement les nombres premiers. Aide: commencez par créer une fonction qui calcule si un nombre entier est un nombre premier (c.a.d., qu’il n'est pas divisible par 2,3,4,5.... ni par sqrt(n), où n est le nombre testé).\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "c7908780",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def is_prime(n):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Check if a given number is prime.\"\"\"\n",
    "    return n > 1 and all(n % i for i in range(2, int(math.sqrt(n)) + 1))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Vectorize the function to apply it on a numpy array.\n",
    "# This will return a mask that we can apply on the original array.\n",
    "is_prime_np = np.vectorize(is_prime)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "74d408d6",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "x = np.arange(10001) # Augmenter le nombre de valeurs pour observer les différences de temps. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "687d91aa",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "42.4 ms ± 2.4 ms per loop (mean ± std. dev. of 7 runs, 10 loops each)\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "%%timeit\n",
    "y = x[is_prime_np(x)]\n",
    "#print(y)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "f99f047c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "83.3 ms ± 5.52 ms per loop (mean ± std. dev. of 7 runs, 10 loops each)\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "%%timeit\n",
    "# Ou alors appliquer la fonction is_prime() dans une compréhensive list: \n",
    "y = [num for num in x if is_prime(num)]\n",
    "#print(y)"
   ]

    "### IV. Calcul d'un histogramme en Python\n",
    "\n",
    "Programmez une fonction en Python qui reçoit en entrée un numpy array et donne en sortie un array indiquant des fréquences de valeurs. Supposez que l’histogramme génère par défaut la fréquence des valeurs dans 10 bins espacées de manière uniforme entre le min et le max des valeurs de l’array numpy en entrée. Générez u n bar chart pour visualiser l’histogramme. Comparez votre résultat avec la fonction hist() de numpy."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 26,
   "id": "0ecd321a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from collections import Counter\n",
    "from typing import Tuple\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def compute_frequency(data: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[np.ndarray, np.ndarray]:\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Compute the frequency of each item.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Parameters\n",
    "    ----------\n",
    "    data : np.ndarray\n",
    "        Original data to compute the frequency from.\n",
    "        \n",
    "    Returns\n",
    "    -------\n",
    "    Tuple of two numpy arrays\n",
    "        Tuple with two numpy arrays. The first numpy array contains the unique values \n",
    "        and the second one their count.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    return np.unique(data, return_counts=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def compute_hist(data: np.ndarray, bins: int = 10) -> Tuple[np.ndarray, np.ndarray]:\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Compute the histogram.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Parameters\n",
    "    ----------\n",
    "    data : np.ndarray\n",
    "        Original data to compute the histogram from.\n",
    "    bins : int, default 10\n",
    "        Number of bins to use in the histogram.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Returns\n",
    "    -------\n",
    "    Tuple of two numpy arrays\n",
    "        Tuple with two numpy arrays. The first numpy array contains the number of element for each bins\n",
    "        and the second one the limit of the bins.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    values, freqs = compute_frequency(data)\n",
    "    bins_edges = np.linspace(values.min(), values.max(), bins + 1)\n",
    "    counts = np.zeros(bins + 1)\n",
    "        \n",
    "    # Look in which bin each value is.\n",
    "    for v, f in zip(values, freqs):\n",
    "        counts[np.searchsorted(bins_edges, v)] += f\n",
    "        \n",
    "    return counts, bins_edges"
   ]
  },
